  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f8128281-b61f-4384-b147-efc8f187b3d1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Which preprocessing steps were essential? Median imputation for missing numeric values (Engine HP, Engine Cylinders, Number of Doors), constant imputation plus one-hot encoding for categoricals (Market Category alone was missing in about 31% of rows), and feature scaling for the linear model.\n",
    "\n",
    "Which model performed best, and why? Random Forest, by a wide margin (validation MAE about \n",
    "9,733 for Linear Regression). Price rises non-linearly with horsepower and cylinder count, especially at the high end, and a tree ensemble captures those non-linearities and feature interactions that a linear model cannot.\n",
    "\n",
    "Did hyperparameter tuning improve performance? Not over the untuned baseline in this case: both GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV converged to the same setting (100 trees, unlimited depth) that was already used as the baseline, so no further gain was found within the searched grid.\n",
    "\n",
    "Which features contributed most? Engine HP dominates (about 60% of Random Forest feature importance), followed by city mpg, Engine Cylinders, Popularity, and the engineered Car_Age feature.\n",
    "\n",
    "What additional data would improve predictions? Curb weight, 0-60 time, trim/options details, and a brand-prestige indicator would likely help the model on the ultra-expensive exotic cars it currently underestimates.\n",
    "\n",
    "Deployment challenges? Handling unseen Makes/Models and new Market Category values not seen in training, price drift over time since the data only goes up to 2017, and the model's weak extrapolation to extremely rare, extremely expensive vehicles."
   ]
  },
